-- Section 1: Georgia O''Keeffe (Q1-13)
-- ============================================
'Georgia O''Keeffe is widely regarded as one of the most significant American artists of the 20th century. Born in 1887 on a farm in Wisconsin, she knew from an early age that she wanted to become an artist. After studying at the Art Institute of Chicago, she initially worked as a teacher while continuing to develop her own artistic style.

O''Keeffe''s early experiments in abstraction caught the attention of Alfred Stieglitz, a renowned photographer and gallery owner in New York. Without her knowledge, Stieglitz exhibited a series of her charcoal drawings at his gallery in 1916. When O''Keeffe confronted him, a relationship began that would shape both of their lives — they later married.

In the 1920s, O''Keeffe began creating the large-scale paintings of flowers for which she would become most famous. These works, which magnified tiny blossoms to fill entire canvases, were unlike anything seen before. She also became captivated by the skyscrapers of New York City, painting them with a precision that captured the energy of modern urban life.

In 1929, O''Keeffe made her first trip to New Mexico, and the landscape there would come to define the rest of her artistic career. The vast desert expanses, dramatic rock formations, and the bright, clear light of the region inspired some of her most celebrated paintings. She was also deeply fascinated by the bones she found scattered across the desert, which she saw not as symbols of death but as evidence of the enduring beauty of the natural world.

O''Keeffe was remarkably productive well into her later years. Even as her eyesight began to fail in the 1970s, she continued to create art with the help of assistants. She also took up working with clay, producing sculptures and pots. She spent her final years in Santa Fe, New Mexico, where the landscape continued to inspire her until her death in 1986 at the age of 98. Today, her work continues to command record prices at auction, and her legacy as one of the most original voices in American art is secure.', NOW());


